posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
Am I the asshole for not wanting coal for Christmas?

This year I went to my fiancé’s house for Christmas. It was my first time going, as we would typically go to my family’s house instead.

I got a (rather pricey) gift for my fiancé “Dan” related to his hobbies, I got nice gifts for “Dan’s” parents based off of things I’d talked about with them before, and I got a small pack of chocolates for each of Dan’s other relatives (I didn’t know them that well).

I wasn’t expecting many gifts from Dan’s relative’s because I didn’t know many of them that well, but I was certainly expecting more than I got.

At first, I was excited when I saw that there was a big pile of gifts for me. However, once I opened the first one it was just a piece of coal. Everyone laughed, and I just kind of laughed along thinking it was a gag gift and that the other gifts would be different. But every single one turned out to be coal. All 18 of them.

I started to get upset, so I cried and lashed out at Dan. But he calmly explained apparently this is a longstanding tradition in his family where they gift coal to newcomers who are celebrating Christmas with them for the first time. He explained that it’s just easier that way since all the relatives who might not know the newcomer well don’t have to stress over finding a gift, and it’s a fun experience for the newcomer as well.

I told Dan I couldn’t believe I skipped my own family’s celebration for this and left. But now Dan and some of his family are blowing up my phone saying I embarrassed him in front of his relatives and that I made it awkward for everyone.

So am I the asshole?

I am so glad they ask because it gives me an opportunity to talk about one of my favorite subjects. I usually respond by first telling them what an Aggie is NOT. An Aggie is not a pig or hog, as they are called in the Ozarks. An Aggie is not a horse, such as the one representing that school out in West Texas. An Aggie is not a pony, like the one in "SMUland." We are certainly not a frog or horned toad, nor a Waco bruin or bear. We are not a little ol' cat or a fowl owl like those in Houston. Most definitely, we are not of the long-horned cattle variety. If we were, we would be a bull or a cow rather than some non-productive steer. (Since a steer is non-productive, and t.u. chooses to be represented by a steer, then logic would follow that t.u. must consider themselves...Hey, don't get mad at me or say, "that's a little strong." I didn't pick their mascot, they did.)

The fact is that an Aggie is not any type of animal. We have Reveille, who is our 1st Lady, but we're not the Texas A&M Reveilles. We're the Aggies. An Aggie is a human. When I think of an Aggie, I think of church, community, and state leaders. I think of the many Aggies who have sacrificed their lives as defenders of freedom through their service to the United States of America.

>>127849802
Why don't people do their research before they post?

Maradona came to Napoli when they had placed 10th and 12th in the previous seasons. In the next season he took them ro 8th. In the next 4 seasons they placed 1st, 2nd, 2nd and 1st. In the next season he was banned for cocaine and the team placed 8th. He left and Napoli fell down to Serie B a few years later. They would never again win another title, Diego won them the only 2 Serie A titles in their history. They would never again reach the top 3 until the 2010s. Maradona was of course among the top goalscorers during this time period despite being a midfielder.

Diego also won the Uefa cup at a time where it was actually a legitimate competition since the European cup was only reserved to the champion of each country. 2nd, 3rd and 4th placed teams playing CL football now where playing Uefa cup back then. Of course winning the European cup would have been more impressive but a player can only so much. He played in the EC twice in his career - and he was banned for drugs halfway through the second time -, as opposed to players now who play CL football almost every season.

This alone would make his club career amazing. You don't see Messi or Ronaldo carrying Almeria, Brighton or Clement to national or Europa League titles. But of course Diego has an impressive international career as well - being the player of the tournament in 86 and carrying an Argentina squad full of scrubs that almost failed to qualify with his 10 goal contributions, most likely the most impressive world cup run by a single player ever made. Much less is talked about his less impactful but still impressive 1990 run where he made the final again.

In terms of individual awards, he was not eligible for the Ballon D'Or but after revision including non europeans, France Football awarded him 2. You can argue longevity all you want since Maradona's peak was somewhat short lived but you can't deny his presence in the top 4 of the sport.

Why don't they just make continental and global divisions instead of cups?

Think about it, your team finishes as 1st in the highest level of football in your country, so next year, it gets promoted to the Continental Division, where your team will face teams from other country every week. And if your team finishes at the top of the Continental Division, it gets promoted to the Global Division.

>b-b--b-but the scheduling and the travelling
They can easily balance that with fewer teams and a softer schedule. The teams are still playing against far better competition and the money they would make from those games would probably be huge than just playing local rivals. And they can still participate in local cups or send a B team to the national tournament.

We would finally have something better than the Club World Cup. UEFA Euro Championship and Libertadores would be replaced by something far fairer. Also, we would be seeing basically what (((they))) wanted to implement when (((they))) tried to pull off the SuperLeague bullshit, but without all the cons, only the pros.

Now, besides the obvious logistic problems that could be discussed and worked on, what's wrong with this idea? Why haven't they tried it?

Imagine seeing your 4th division team go to the 3rd, then 2nd, then 1st division, then win it all and go to the continental division and then the global division where you will see them face teams like Barcelona, Real, Man Utd, Man City, PSG every other week

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
"Passionate fans" and hooligans are distinct, as hooliganism necessitates violence. Organized vocal supporters are better described as "Ultras," though many people/groups will describe themselves as or both.

As for how serious they are, it varies. Some hool groups will be fairly informal, and group membership isn't even technically necessary- a supporter who happens to get into fights might accurately be described as a hool. Under a stricter definition, there will be some type of membership required. For some groups, their activity is limited to supporting sport clubs, and fighting. Other times they are involved in more serious criminal activities, and might be classified as organized crime groups, or political street militias.

Things are generally the most serious in former communist Europe, with Russia seemingly the most violent. Among non-former-commie countries, maybe Greece is the worst, though it's mostly limited to Athens. Italy seems to have a strong culture, but it's more on the ultra-side of things. Surprisingly, Sweden has developed a decently violent scene in the past 20 or so years. I can't speak for the Islamic world.

South America also has a strong hooligan culture, though they don't often use the term. The violence can be more intense, though they don't seem to do arranged fights as often as in Europe. Correct me if I'm wrong.

The "glory days" of British hooliganism are long gone. Many of the old firms* still exist, but their profile is diminished, the police know who they are, and they're often banned from sporting events.

*an organized hooligan group
